46: /**
47:  * Coordinates the timing of animations, input and drawing.
48:  * <p>
49:  * The choreographer receives timing pulses (such as vertical synchronization)
50:  * from the display subsystem then schedules work to occur as part of rendering
51:  * the next display frame.
52:  * </p><p>
53:  * Applications typically interact with the choreographer indirectly using
54:  * higher level abstractions in the animation framework or the view hierarchy.
55:  * Here are some examples of things you can do using the higher-level APIs.
56:  * </p>
57:  * <ul>
58:  * <li>To post an animation to be processed on a regular time basis synchronized with
59:  * display frame rendering, use {@link android.animation.ValueAnimator#start}.</li>
60:  * <li>To post a {@link Runnable} to be invoked once at the beginning of the next display
61:  * frame, use {@link View#postOnAnimation}.</li>
62:  * <li>To post a {@link Runnable} to be invoked once at the beginning of the next display
63:  * frame after a delay, use {@link View#postOnAnimationDelayed}.</li>
64:  * <li>To post a call to {@link View#invalidate()} to occur once at the beginning of the
65:  * next display frame, use {@link View#postInvalidateOnAnimation()} or
66:  * {@link View#postInvalidateOnAnimation(int, int, int, int)}.</li>
67:  * <li>To ensure that the contents of a {@link View} scroll smoothly and are drawn in
68:  * sync with display frame rendering, do nothing.  This already happens automatically.
69:  * {@link View#onDraw} will be called at the appropriate time.</li>
70:  * </ul>
71:  * <p>
72:  * However, there are a few cases where you might want to use the functions of the
73:  * choreographer directly in your application.  Here are some examples.
74:  * </p>
75:  * <ul>
76:  * <li>If your application does its rendering in a different thread, possibly using GL,
77:  * or does not use the animation framework or view hierarchy at all
78:  * and you want to ensure that it is appropriately synchronized with the display, then use
79:  * {@link Choreographer#postFrameCallback}.</li>
80:  * <li>... and that's about it.</li>
81:  * </ul>
82:  * <p>
83:  * Each {@link Looper} thread has its own choreographer.  Other threads can
84:  * post callbacks to run on the choreographer but they will run on the {@link Looper}
85:  * to which the choreographer belongs.
86:  * </p>
87:  */
88: public final class Choreographer {
89:     private static final String TAG = "Choreographer";
90: 
91:     // Prints debug messages about jank which was detected (low volume).
92:     private static final boolean DEBUG_JANK = false;
93: 
94:     // Prints debug messages about every frame and callback registered (high volume).
95:     private static final boolean DEBUG_FRAMES = false;
96: 
97:     // The default amount of time in ms between animation frames.
98:     // When vsync is not enabled, we want to have some idea of how long we should
99:     // wait before posting the next animation message.  It is important that the
100:     // default value be less than the true inter-frame delay on all devices to avoid
101:     // situations where we might skip frames by waiting too long (we must compensate
102:     // for jitter and hardware variations).  Regardless of this value, the animation
103:     // and display loop is ultimately rate-limited by how fast new graphics buffers can
